{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Galactosialidosis | synonyms = | image = Autosomal recessive - en.svg | caption = Galactosialidosis is inherited in a autosomal recessive manner | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Galactosialidosis''' is a [[lysosomal storage disease]].<ref name="pmid18429828">{{cite journal |vauthors=Koike K, Hamaguchi T, Kitamura H, Imasawa T, Joh K |title=Galactosialidosis associated with IgA nephropathy: morphological study of renal biopsy |journal=Pathol. Int. |volume=58 |issue=5 |pages=295–9 |year=2008 |pmid=18429828 |doi=10.1111/j.1440-1827.2008.02226.x |url=http://www.blackwell-synergy.com/openurl?genre=article&sid=nlm:pubmed&issn=1320-5463&date=2008&volume=58&issue=5&spage=295}}</ref> This condition is rare and most cases have been in the juvenile/adult group of patients. An infantile form has been described.
==Molecular biology==
It is associated with [[cathepsin A]].<ref name="pmid8725271">{{cite journal |author=Kleijer WJ |title=Cathepsin A deficiency in galactosialidosis: studies of patients and carriers in 16 families |journal=Pediatr. Res. |volume=39 |issue=6 |pages=1067–71 |year=1996 |pmid=8725271 |doi= 10.1203/00006450-199606000-00022|url=http://meta.wkhealth.com/pt/pt-core/template-journal/lwwgateway/media/landingpage.htm?issn=0031-3998&volume=39&issue=6&spage=1067 |name-list-format=vanc |author2=Geilen GC |author3=Janse HC |display-authors=3 |last4=Van Diggelen |first4=O. P. |last5=Zhou |first5=Xiao YAN |last6=Galjart |first6=N. J. |last7=Galjaard |first7=H. |last8=d'Azzo |first8=A.}}</ref> This disease is due to mutations in the CTSA gene which encodes the protective protein/cathepsin A (PPCA).<ref name=Caciotti2013>{{cite journal | author = Caciotti A, Catarzi S, Tonin R, Lugli L, Perez CR, Michelakakis H, Mavridou I, Donati MA, Guerrini R, D'Azzo A, Morrone A | year = 2013 | title = Galactosialidosis: review and analysis of CTSA gene mutations | pmc = 3737020 | journal = Orphanet J Rare Dis | volume = 8 | issue = 1| page = 114 | pmid=23915561 | doi=10.1186/1750-1172-8-114}}</ref> This in turn leads to a secondary deficiency of [[beta-galactosidase]] (GLB1) and [[neuraminidase]] 1 (NEU1).{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}There are three distinct CTSA isoforms.
==Diagnosis== A [[prenatal]] diagnosis was made by Kleijer et al. in 1979 by measuring [[beta-galactosidase]] and [[neuraminidase]] activities in cultured [[amniotic fluid]] cells.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kleijer |first=W. J. |last2=Hoogeveen |first2=A. |last3=Verheijen |first3=F. W. |last4=Niermeijer |first4=M. F. |last5=Galjaard |first5=H. |last6=O'Brien |first6=J. S. |last7=Warner |first7=T. G. |date=July 1979 |title=Prenatal diagnosis of sialidosis with combined neuraminidase and beta-galactosidase deficiency |journal=Clinical Genetics |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=60–61 |issn=0009-9163 |pmid=477017 |doi=10.1111/j.1399-0004.1979.tb00851.x}}</ref>
