{{Use Indian English|date=November 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}} {{Infobox historic site | name = Nimtala crematorium | native_name = নিমতলা মহাশ্মশান | native_language = bn | image = Nimtala burning ghat, Calcutta in 1945.jpg | caption =The Nimtala burning ghat in 1945. | locmapin = | location = 2p, Strand Bank Road, Beadon Street, [[Kolkata]] – 700006 | area = Beadon Street | built = | architect = | architecture = | governing_body = | designation1 = | designation1_offname = | designation1_date = | designation1_number = | designation2 = | designation2_offname = | designation2_date = | designation2_number = | designation3 = | designation3_offname = | designation3_date = | designation3_number = | designation4 = | designation4_offname = | designation4_date = | designation4_number = | designation5 = | designation5_offname = | designation5_date = | designation5_number = }} '''Nimtala crematorium''' or '''Nimtala burning ghat''' or '''Nimtala ghat''' is a [[crematory]] located at Beadon Street, [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal, India]].<ref name="Chatterji1968">{{cite book|author=Sudhamoy Chatterji|title=Death and after|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-UtAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=16 December 2012|year=1968|publisher=Firma K. L. Mukhopadhyay|page=110}}</ref>
== History == The burning ghat came up in 1827. In 2010 the central government of India rejuvenated and upgraded the crematorium which cost {{INRConvert|140|m}}. [[Rabindranath Tagore]] was cremated here (north Calcutta burning ghat). There is a Rabindranath Tagore Memorial in the crematorium compound which was beautified in the 2010 project.<ref name="Rs 14cr upgrade for Nimtala burning ghat">{{cite news|title=Rs 14cr upgrade for Nimtala burning ghat|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100309/jsp/calcutta/story_12189585.jsp|accessdate=16 December 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph Calcutta}}</ref>
The ghat has also represented in popular literature, in the famous [[Sahitya Akademi Award]] winning Malayalam novel by [[K. R. Meera]], [[Aarachaar]] Nimtala Crematorium is a significant part of the plot.
Legend has it, that atleast one deceased must be cremated there or else all the [[Pyre|funeral pyres]] catch fire and incinerate. It is also believed that water cannot extinguish those pyres, if such an incident ever occurs.
